<chapter xml:id="chapter-funcs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Functions and graphs</title>

<section xml:id="section-funcs-intro">
<title>Basics</title>

<p>
A function is an <em>input-output</em> process.
While more generally a function definition can specify <em>any</em> kind of input and <em>any</em> kind of output,
for us a function will always be <em>one number in, one number out</em>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-input-output-schematic">
	<caption> Schematic of a function as an input-output process. </caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-in-out" width="60.2%">
		<shortdescription>Schematic of a function as an input-output process.</shortdescription>
		<!-- TODO description -->
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/in-out.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
There are three components to function notation <m>f(t)</m>:
<dl>

	<li>
		<title>input</title>
		<p>
		The input value is represented by the independent variable <m>t</m> and is placed inside parentheses.
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>output</title>
		<p>
		The full expression <m>f(t)</m> represents the output value that corresponds to the particular input value <m>t</m>.
		</p>
	</li>

	<li>
		<title>name</title>
		<p>
		The name of a function is often represented by the letter <m>f</m>
		(for <em>f</em>unction),
		but other letters can be used.
		</p>
	</li>

</dl>
Some functions have special names;
for example:
<ul>
	<li>
		<m>\sin</m>, <m>\cos</m>, and <m>\tan</m> for the trigonometric sine, cosine, and tangent functions
	</li>
	<li>
		<m>\ln</m> and <m>\exp</m> for the natural logarithm and exponential functions.
	</li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>
	<alert>A function is not a formula.</alert>
	A formula is just one way to describe the input-output process of a function,
	but there are other ways to do so, including:
	<ul>
		<li> a table of values </li>
		<li> a graph </li>
		<li> a description in words. </li>
	</ul>
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-by-table">
	<title>A function defined by a table of values</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>f</m> represent the function produces outputs <m>f(t)</m> from inputs <m>t</m> according to the following table.
	</p>
	<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
		<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>t</m></cell>
				<cell><m>0</m></cell>
				<cell><m>1</m></cell>
				<cell><m>2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>3</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\pi</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
				<cell><m>f(t)</m></cell>
				<cell><m>0</m></cell>
				<cell><m>1/3</m></cell>
				<cell><m>-2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\sqrt{5}</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>
	<p>
	For example,
	the table says that <m>f(1) = 1/3</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-by-desc">
	<title>A function defined by a description</title>
	<p>
	A device that measures wind speed is called an <term>anemometer</term>.
	Suppose an anemometer is set up in the quad of the Augustana Campus.
	For <m>t</m> representing time measured in seconds from the instant the anemometer is fully set up and operational,
	let <m>w(t)</m> represent the wind speed measured by the device at time <m>t</m>,
	in kilometres per hour.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
It would be pretty difficult to come up with a formula in <m>t</m> that describes the function in <xref ref="example-funcs-by-desc" />.
However, as we'll see in <xref ref="example-funcs-piecewise-table" />,
it's possible (but tedious) to create a <q>formula</q> for a function that has initially been defined by a table of values,
as in <xref ref="example-funcs-by-table" />.
</p>

<p>
The information in <xref ref="example-funcs-by-table" /> seems incomplete <mdash />
how can we determine <m>f(-1)</m> or <m>f(1/2)</m> from the table?
Since the function description does not specify how to determine output values for these inputs,
we must accept that there are no such output values <m>f(-1)</m> and <m>f(1/2)</m>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-funcs-domain">
	<title>Domain of a function</title>
	<statement><p>
		The set of all values of the independent variable <m>t</m> that can be used as an input value for the function,
		in the sense that there is an associated output value.
		For values of <m>t</m> that are not in the domain,
		we say that the output value <m>f(t)</m> is <term>undefined</term>.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-domain-table-and-desc">

	<p>
	If we assume that the anemometer in <xref ref="example-funcs-by-desc" /> could continuously record wind speed measurements,
	then the domain of the <m>w</m> function in that example is <m>t \ge 0</m>,
	and the function is undefined for <m>t \lt 0</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	The domain of the function <m>f</m> from <xref ref="example-funcs-by-table" /> is merely the set of values <m> t = 0, 1, 2, 3, \pi </m>,
	and <m>f(t)</m> is undefined for all other values of <m>t</m>.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
Technically,
the domain of a function is part of its definition,
but it is often not explicitly specified.
In that case,
we should assume that the domain is as large as possible,
and includes all possible input values that <q>make sense</q> in the function definition.
</p>

<example>
	<title>An implicit domain</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>f</m> represent the function described by the input-output formula
	<me> f(t) = \frac{1}{t} </me>.
	The domain of this function is <m>t \neq 0</m>,
	meaning the set of all input values <em>except</em> <m>t = 0</m>,
	since at <m>t = 0</m> the output formula would involve division by zero.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
However,
sometimes we want to restrict the possible input values for some reason,
even if the description of the function's input-output process could allow other input values.
</p>

<example>
	<title>A restricted domain</title>
	<p>
	Let <m>f</m> represent the function
	<md><mrow> f(t) \amp = t^2 \amp t \amp \ge 0 </mrow></md>.
	Here the domain is explicitly specified as being <m>t \ge 0</m>.
	So even though the formula <m>(-1)^2</m> is defined,
	technically the output value <m>f(-1)</m> is <em>undefined</em> because we have specified in the function definition that the input-output formula <m>t \mapsto t^2</m> only applies for <m>t \ge 0</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p> We often also want to determine the <term>range</term> of possible output values of a function. </p>

<definition xml:id="definition-funcs-range">
	<title>Range of a function</title>
	<statement><p> The set of all output values that can be achieved by a function. </p></statement>
</definition>

<example><p>
	The function <me> f(t) = \frac{1}{t^2} </me> only outputs positive values.
	But is every positive value an <em>actual</em> output of the function?
	Yes, because if <m>y</m> is a positive number,
	there is at least one example of an input value so that <m>f(t) = y</m>;
	in particular,
	<md><mrow>
		t \amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{y}}
		\amp
		f(t) \amp = \frac{1}{{1/\sqrt{y}}^2} = y
	</mrow></md>.
	So the range of this function is the set of all positive numbers.
</p></example>

<example>
	<title>A restricted domain could restrict the range</title>
	<p>
	The function <m>f(t) = t^3</m> has the entire set of real numbers <m>\R</m> for its range,
	as every real number is the cube of another number.
	However,
	the function
	<md><mrow> g(t) \amp = t^3 \amp t \amp \ge 0 </mrow></md>
	has range <m> g(t) \ge 0 </m>,
	since by discarding negative inputs we will no longer achieve any negative outputs.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Graph of a function</title>

<definition xml:id="definition-funcs-graph">
	<title>Graph of a function</title>
	<statement><p> The collection of all input-output pairs <m>\bbrac{t, f(t)}</m> in the Cartesian plane. </p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
For a point <m>(t,y)</m> in the Cartesian plane,
the property of being on the graph or not on the graph of a function <m>f</m> is precisely determined by whether or not <m>f(t) = y</m> is true.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Parabola</title>

	<p> The graph of the function <m>f(t) = t^2</m> creates a curve in a shape called a <term>parabola</term>. </p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-parabola">
		<caption>
			The parabolic graph of the function <m>f(t) = t^2</m>,
			including two representative points:
			one on the graph and one not on the graph.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-parabola" width="67.9%">
			<shortdescription> Parabolic graph of the basic quadratic function. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/parabola.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	In <xref ref="figure-funcs-parabola" />,
	the point <m>(2,4)</m> appears on the graph because for <m>t = 2</m> and <m>y = 4</m>,
	the equality <m>f(t) = y</m> is true,
	whereas the point <m>(-1,6)</m> appears displaced from the graph because for <m>t = -1</m> and <m>y = 6</m>,
	the equality <m>f(t) = y</m> is not true.
	</p>

</example>

<p> A graph is not necessarily a curve. </p>

<example>
	<title>A graph as a collection of points</title>

	<p>
	Consider again the function in <xref ref="example-funcs-by-table" />,
	which was defined by a table of values.
	Since the table only defines five input-output pairs,
	the graph consists of only five isolated points.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-discrete">
		<caption> An example graph that consists of only five points. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-discrete" width="34.7%">
			<shortdescription> An example graph that consists of only five points. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/discrete.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
Every function can be associated with a collection of points in the Cartesian plane representing input-output pairs,
and for many of the functions we study this collection of points will <q>join together</q> to form a curve.
Is the opposite true?
Is every curve in the Cartesian plane the graph of a function?
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-funcs-VLT">
	<title>Vertical Line Test</title>
	<p> A curve in the Cartesian plane is the graph of a function if and only if every vertical line intersects the graph only once or not at all. </p>
</identity>

<p>
The <q>only once</q> part of <xref ref="pattern-funcs-VLT" /> represents the fact that a function should associate one and only one output value to each input value in the domain.
If some vertical line intersects the curve more than once,
then those intersection points associate different output values to the same input value,
which a function cannot do.
The <q>or not at all</q> part of <xref ref="pattern-funcs-VLT" /> covers the situation of a vertical line at a <m>t</m>-position that is not in the domain of the function,
in which case there is no corresponding point on the graph for a vertical line at that <m>t</m>-position to intersect.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-VLT">
	<caption> Illustrations of the Vertical Line Test. </caption>

	<sidebyside widths="42.9% 36.7%">

		<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-VLT-1">
			<caption> A curve that passes the Vertical Line Test. </caption>
			<image xml:id="image-funcs-vlt1">
				<shortdescription> A curve that passes the Vertical Line Test. </shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/vlt1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-VLT-2">
			<caption> A curve that does not pass the Vertical Line Test. </caption>
			<image xml:id="image-funcs-vlt2">
				<shortdescription> A curve that does not pass the Vertical Line Test. </shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/vlt2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

	</sidebyside>

</figure>

<p>
If a curve passes the Vertical Line Test,
of what function will it be the graph?
Remember that a function can be described as an input-output process in several different ways.
To describe a function via a graph,
assign an output value <m>f(t)</m> to each input value <m>t</m> as follows:
<ul>

	<li>
		if the vertical line at position <m>t</m> does not intersect the graph,
		leave <m>f(t)</m> undefined
	</li>

	<li>
		if the vertical line at position <m>t</m> does intersect the graph and the graph passes the Vertical Line Test,
		then we can assume that there is only one such point of intersection,
		so set <m>f(t)</m> to be the second coordinate of that point.
	</li>

</ul>
</p>

</section>

<section>
<title>Piecewise functions</title>

<p>
Sometimes we want to <q>stitch together</q> several formulas,
so that one formula applies to one subdomain,
another formula applies to another subdomain,
and so on.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-commissions">
	<title>Salary with commission</title>

	<p>
	Salespeople at a particular store make a base salary of $4000 per month,
	on top of which they make a $10 commission on every unit they sell.
	As an additional incentive,
	after the first 100 units they sell in a month,
	the commission on additional units sold is $15.
	</p>

	<p>
	Let <m>q</m> represent the number of units sold in a month by any one salesperson,
	and let <m>s(q)</m> represent the salary to be paid to that employee.
	In the domain <m> 0 \le q \le 100 </m> we have <me> s(q) = 4000 + 10 q </me>.
	But on the domain <m> q \gt 100 </m> we have <me> s(q) = 4000 + 10 q + 5 (q - 100) </me>.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
We can collect together several formulas into one function definition with some notation.
For example,
the salary function from <xref ref="example-funcs-commissions" /> can be expressed as
<me>
	s(q) = \begin{cases}
		4000 + 10 q \amp 0 \le q \le 100 \\
		4000 + 10 q + 5 (q - 100) \amp q \gt 100
	\end{cases}
</me>.
The format of this notation begins with a large left brace,
which alerts the reader that the formulas on the right are to be grouped together as cases in the definition of the function.
Then we have the formulas and their associated domain of application,
one per line.
It's important that the subdomains don't overlap,
so that we haven't defined a particular output value in more than one way.
However, there is no requirement that the subdomains meet <mdash />
the function can be left undefined at input values between the subdomains.
</p>

<p>
A function that is defined in pieces in this way is called,
fittingly,
a <term>piecewise function</term>.
As you can imagine, a piecewise function will also have a graph that appears to be built out of pieces.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-piecewise-graph">
	<title>Graph of a piecewise function</title>

	<p>
	Consider the piecewise function
	<me>
		f(t) = \begin{cases}
			t^2 \amp 0 \le t \le 2 \\
			6 - t \amp t \gt 2
		\end{cases}
	</me>,
	the graph of which appears in <xref ref="figure-funcs-piecewise" />.
	Notice how the graph is made of part parabola,
	and part line.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-piecewise">
		<caption> Graph of a piecewise-defined function. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-piecewise" width="47%">
			<shortdescription> Graph of a piecewise-defined function. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/piecewise.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
When creating a piecewise-defined function,
there is no requirement that the pieces of the graph meet at the transition points.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-piecewise-graph-2">
	<title>A piecewise function with a <q>jump</q> in its graph</title>

	<p>
	Now consider the piecewise function
	<me>
		g(t) = \begin{cases}
			t^2 \amp 0 \le t \le 2 \\
			4 - t \amp t \gt 2
		\end{cases}
	</me>,
	the graph of which appears in <xref ref="figure-funcs-piecewise-2" />.
	At <m>t = 2</m>,
	the parabola portion on the left ends at height <m>4</m> but the line begins at height <m>2</m>,
	so the two <q>pieces</q> of graph do not meet at the transition point.
	Also notice that we have drawn a closed point at <m>(2,4)</m> at the <q>end</q> of the parabola portion of the graph,
	but have drawn an open point at <m>(2,2)</m> at the <q>beginning</q> of the line portion.
	This represents the fact that the parabola subdomain <m>0 \le t \le 2</m> contains the input value <m>t = 2</m> while the line subdomain <m>t \gt 2</m> does not,
	so the piecewise definition dictates that the formula <m>g(t) = t^2</m> applies when <m>t = 2</m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-piecewise-2">
		<caption> Graph of a piecewise-defined function with a <q>jump</q> in values. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-piecewise-2" width="47%">
			<shortdescription> Graph of a piecewise-defined function with a "jump" in values. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/piecewise-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p> A piecewise-defined function can be built out of more than two pieces. </p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-piecewise-many">
	<title>A piecewise function in many pieces</title>

	<p>
	Now consider the piecewise function
	<me>
		h(t) = \begin{cases}
			0 \amp t \lt 0 \\
			t^2 \amp 0 \le t \le 2 \\
			5 \amp 2 \lt t \lt 3 \\
			10 - 2 t \amp 3 \le t \le 5 \\
			0 \amp t \gt 5
		\end{cases}
	</me>,
	the graph of which appears in <xref ref="figure-funcs-piecewise-many" />.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-piecewise-many">
		<caption> Graph of a piecewise-defined function with many pieces. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-piecewise-many" width="67.9%">
			<shortdescription> Graph of a piecewise-defined function with many pieces. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/piecewise-many.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
We can use this notation to define a <q>formula</q> for a function that as been defined by a table of values,
but it is not really any different than writing down a table of values.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-piecewise-table">
	<title>Piecewise table of values</title>
	<p>
	Here is the function from <xref ref="example-funcs-by-table" /> in piecewise-function notation.
	<me>
		f(t) = \begin{cases}
			0 \amp t = 0 \\
			1/3 \amp t = 1 \\
			-2 \amp t = 2 \\
			2 \amp t = 3 \\
			\sqrt{5} \amp t = \pi
		\end{cases}
	</me>.
	This function is still only defined at a handful of points <mdash />
	for example, <m>f(1/2)</m> is undefined because there is no listed formula whose associated subdomain is or contains <m>t = 1/2</m>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-funcs-cont">
<title>Continuous functions</title>

<introduction><p>
	The graphs in <xref ref="figure-funcs-piecewise-2" />
	and <xref ref="figure-funcs-piecewise-many" />
	have an odd feature <mdash />
	they approach one value then suddenly jump to a different value.
	We'll call this type of feature a <term>point of discontinuity</term>.
</p></introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Definition</title>

<definition xml:id="definition-funcs-point-continuous">
	<title>Continuous at a point</title>
	<statement><p>
		A function <m>f(t)</m> is said to be <term>continuous at a specific input value</term> <m>t = t_0</m> if the values of <m>f(t)</m> can always be restricted to being within some arbitrarily small open range around the value <m>f(t_0)</m> by restricting the inputs <m>t</m> to some sufficiently small open subdomain around <m>t_0</m>.
		Otherwise, the function is said to be <term>discontinuous</term> at that point.
	</p></statement>
</definition>

<p>
In other words,
a function is continuous at a point if <m>f(t) \approx f(t_0)</m> whenever <m>t \approx t_0</m>,
and we can always make the first approximation better by tightening the second approximation.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Testing the definition of continuity</title>

	<p>
	The function <m>f(t)</m> in <xref ref="example-funcs-piecewise-graph-2" /> is discontinuous at <m>t = 2</m>.
	It has value <m>f(2) = 4</m> there,
	but if <m>t</m> is slightly bigger than <m>2</m> then <m>f(t) \approx 2</m>, not <m>4</m>.
	So it's not possible to restrict output values to the open range
	<me> 3 \lt f(t) \lt 5 </me>
	around the actual output value <m>f(2) = 4</m>.
	That is, when we take <m>f(t) \approx 4</m> to mean <q> no lower than <m>3</m> and no higher than <m>5</m></q>,
	there is no way to make this true for all <m>t \approx 2</m>,
	no matter how small a subdomain around <m>t = 2</m> that we take for the meaning of <m>t \approx 2</m>
	because there will always be some <m>t \approx 2</m> with <m>f(t) \approx 2</m>, outside of that restricted range.
	</p>

	<p>
	On the other hand,
	that same function <em>is</em> continuous at <m>t = 1</m>.
	No matter how small a range around <m>f(1) = 1</m> we take <m>f(t) \approx 1</m> to mean,
	it is always possible to restrict <m>t</m> to some small open subdomain around <m>t = 1</m> so that <m>f(t) \approx f(1)</m> is true for all <m>t</m> within that subdomain.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-discont-cont">
		<caption> A point of discontinuity and one of continuity. </caption>

		<sidebyside widths="54.1% 43.5%">

			<figure>
				<caption>
					There will always be values of <m>f(t)</m> for <m>t \approx 2</m>
					(represented by the part of the graph highlighted red),
					that are outside of the range <m>3 \lt f(t) \lt 5</m>,
					no matter how small of a subdomain around <m>t = 2</m> we take <m>t \approx 2</m> to mean.
				</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-funcs-piecewise-2-discont">
					<shortdescription> The graph of a function near a point of discontinuity cannot be restricted to particular output range. </shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/piecewise-2-discont.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure>
				<caption>
					Using <em>any</em> small range around <m>f(1) = 1</m>,
					we can always restrict the domain around <m>t = 1</m> so that <m>f(t) \approx f(1)</m> is true for all <m>t \approx 1</m>.
					(The Greek letter <m>\epsilon</m> in the figure represents a small amount above or below <m>f(1) = 1</m> to create a small range.)
				</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-funcs-piecewise-2-cont">
					<shortdescription>
						The graph of a function near a point of continuity can always be restricted to a small output range,
						no matter how small.
					</shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/piecewise-2-cont.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

	</figure>

</example>

<p>
Graphically,
we think of a function as being continuous at an input value <m>t = t_0</m> if its graph <q>flows through</q> the point <m>\bbrac{t_0, f(t_0)}</m>,
while the graph near a point of discontinuity features some sort of gap or jump.
In particular,
a function will always be discontinuous at a point that is not in its domain,
since then there is no value <m>f(t_0)</m> with which to compare its <q>nearby</q> values.
</p>

<p>
Discussing continuity point-by-point is tedious;
we generally just look for likely spots for discontinuities.
(See below for examples.)
Between discontinuities, we  make a blanket pronouncement of continuity.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-funcs-domain-continuous">
	<title>Continuous on a subdomain</title>

	<statement>

		<p> A function <m>f(t)</m> is said to be <term>continuous on a specific subdomain</term> if it is continuous at every point in that subdomain. </p>

		<p>
		If a function is continuous on its entire domain we will say exactly that:
		the function is <term>continuous on its domain</term>.
		If we just say that a function is <term>continuous</term>,
		we mean that the function is continuous at all real input values.
		</p>

	</statement>

</definition>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Common types of discontinuity</title>

<p> We will encounter three basic types of discontinuities. </p>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Jump discontinuities</title>

	<p>
	This occurs when a function suddenly jumps in value,
	hence the name.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-jump-discont">
		<caption> Two examples of jump discontinuities. </caption>

		<sidebyside widths="38.8% 38.8%">

			<figure>
				<caption> A piecewise function can often (but not always!) jump values at transition points. </caption>
				<image xml:id="image-funcs-jump-discont-1">
					<shortdescription> A piecewise function with a jump discontinuity. </shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/jump-discont-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure>
				<caption>
					Sometimes the output of a function at one specific input location is specially defined,
					creating a jump discontinuity.
				</caption>
				<image xml:id="image-funcs-jump-discont-2">
					<shortdescription> A function with a redefined point creating a jump discontinuity. </shortdescription>
					<!-- TODO description -->
					<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/jump-discont-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

	</figure>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Removable discontinuities</title>

	<p>
	You might think of this kind of discontinuity as a <q>hole in the graph</q>.
	For example, for the function <me> f(t) = \frac{t^2 - 1}{t - 1} </me>,
	for <em>most</em> values of <m>t</m> we can simplify the input-output formula to
	<md>
		<mrow> f(t) \amp = \frac{t^2 - 1}{t - 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{(t + 1) \bcancel{(t - 1)}}{\bcancel{t - 1}} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = t + 1</mrow>
	</md>,
	so that the function's graph is essentially a line.
	But the algebra above is <em>not</em> valid for <m>t = 1</m>,
	because in that case our algebra is
	<md>
		<mrow> \frac{t^2 - 1}{t - 1} \amp = \frac{(t + 1) (t - 1)}{t - 1} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{(2) \bcancel{(0)}}{\bcancel{0}} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 2</mrow>
	</md>,
	which is incorrect because you cannot <q>cancel</q> division by zero.
	So our function is actually undefined at <m>t = 1</m>,
	and its graph just has a hole there.
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption> A graph with a discontinuity caused by an undefined value. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-hole" width="38.8%">
			<shortdescription> A graph with a discontinuity caused by an undefined value. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/hole.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	Why not just define <m>f(t) = t + 1</m> in the first place?
	Our function might be created as the ratio of two other quantities,
	where the numerator is a model for some quantity,
	the denominator is a model for a separate quantity,
	and we want the function to track their ratio.
	In this case,
	it is important to record that the ratio is undefined when the second quantity is zero.
	</p>

	<p>
	However, the fact that <m>f(t) = t + 1</m> is true for <q>almost all</q> input values justifies the terminology <term>removable discontinuity</term> <mdash/>
	we could <q>remove</q> the discontinuity by replacing <m>f(t)</m> by the continuous function <m>g(t) = t + 1</m>,
	so that <m>g(t) = f(t)</m> is true for <q>almost all</q> input values.
	Thus <m>g</m> <q>fixes</q> the discontinuity in <m>f</m>,
	and so is called a <term>continuous extension</term> of <m>f</m>.
	</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs>
	<title>Singularities</title>

	<p>
	Some functions have a different kind of hole in their domain,
	near which the function values <q>explode</q>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-singularity">
		<caption>
			The graph of <m>f(t) = 1/(t - 2)^2</m>,
			with a singularity at <m>t = 2</m>.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-singular" width="51.1%">
			<shortdescription> A graph of a function with a discontinuity caused by a singularity. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/singular.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	We will call such an input location a <term>singularity</term> for the function.
	The vertical line at that location
	(as represented by a dashed line in the example graph in <xref ref="figure-funcs-singularity" />)
	is called a <term>vertical asymptote</term> for the function's graph.
	</p>

	<p> We will study singularities and vertical asymptotes more in <xref ref="chapter-inf-behaviour" />. </p>

</paragraphs>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>The Intermediate Value Theorem</title>

<p> An important feature of continuous graphs is that they cannot <q>skip over</q> any particular output level. </p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-funcs-intermediate-value">
	<title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m>f</m> is a continuous function.
		If <m>f(t_1) \lt K</m> and <m>f(t_2) \gt K</m> (or vice versa),
		then <m>f(t) = K</m> must have at least one solution in the domain <m>t_1 \lt t \lt t_2</m>.
	</p></statement>
</theorem>

<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-IVT">
	<caption>
		As a continuous function ascends/descends,
		it must take on all possible output values between initial and final output values.
	</caption>
	<sidebyside>
		<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-IVT-low-to-high">
			<caption>Ascending through each possible output value.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-funcs-IVT-low-to-high">
				<shortdescription>A continuous function ascending through all possible output values from low to high.</shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/IVT-low-to-high.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-IVT-high-to-low">
			<caption>Descending through each possible output value.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-funcs-IVT-high-to-low">
				<shortdescription>A continuous function descending through all possible output values from high to low.</shortdescription>
				<!-- TODO description -->
				<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/IVT-high-to-low.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</sidebyside>
</figure>

<example>
	<title>Searching for horizontal intercepts</title>

	<p>
	The graph of the cubic function <me> p(t) = 5 - t + t^2 - t^3 </me> is continuous,
	so from the information
	<md>
		<mrow>
			p(1) \amp = 4 \text{,}
			\amp
			p(2) \amp = -1
		</mrow>
	</md>
	we may conclude that the graph must descend through every possible output value between <m>4</m> and <m>-1</m> over the domain <m>1 \le t \le 2</m>.
	(Note, however, that this doesn't mean the graph cannot ascend on some portion of this domain.)
	</p>

	<p>
	In particular,
	since <m>p(1) \gt 0</m> and <m>p(2) \lt 0</m>,
	we may apply the <xref ref="theorem-funcs-intermediate-value" text="title" /> with <m>K = 0</m> to conclude that there must be at least one solution to
	<me> 5 - t + t^2 - t^3 = 0 </me>
	somewhere between <m>t = 1</m> and <m>t = 2</m>.
	</p>

</example>

</subsection>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-funcs-transformations">
<title>Graph transformations</title>


<introduction>

<p>
Sketching graphs by plotting a few points and then connecting the dots is not a good strategy in general,
unless you are a computer and can plot millions of points.
The issue is that you may overlook important features that occur between the points you plotted.
</p>

<p>
For example, consider function <me> f(t) = \frac{2}{2 t - 1} </me>.
On a set of axes,
plot points at integer values of <m>t</m>: <me> t = -2, -1, 0, 1, 2</me>.
Then join your points together smoothly to make a <q>graph</q> for <m>f(t)</m>.
Finally, get an online graphing app to graph <m>f(t)</m> for you and compare with your <q>graph</q> <mdash />
you will find that they are very different.
</p>

<p>
A better strategy is to become familiar with a set family of reference graphs,
and try to interpret graphs of similar functions as transformations of the reference graphs.
We often will still plot a few <q>anchor</q> points to keep track of as we perform the transformations,
but mainly we want to use the relationships between the graph at hand and a reference graph.
</p>

</introduction>

<subsection>
<title>Vertical transformations</title>

<subsubsection>
<title>Vertical shift</title>

<p>
If we take an <q>old</q> function and add some fixed value to every output,
we create a <q>new</q> function whose graph is moved up
(if the added fixed value is positive)
or down
(if the added fixed value is negative).
Accordingly, for
<me> g(t) = f(t) + C </me>,
we call <m>g</m> a <term>vertical shift</term> of <m>f</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-vshift">
	<title>Vertical shifts of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph either of
	<md><mrow> g(t) \amp = \sqrt{t} + 2 \amp h(t) \amp = \sqrt{t} - 2 </mrow></md>,
	we relate each of them to the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>,
	whose graph we should know as one-half of a sideways parabola.
	Some anchor points we might focus on to help us draw the shifted graph are at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(0) \amp = 0             \amp f(1) \amp = 1             </mrow>
		<mrow> g(0) \amp = f(0) + 2 = 2  \amp g(1) \amp = f(1) + 2 = 3  </mrow>
		<mrow> h(0) \amp = f(0) - 2 = -2 \amp h(1) \amp = f(1) - 2 = -1 </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-vshifts">
		<caption>
			Two vertical shifts of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>,
			one up and one down.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-vshifts" width="62.3%">
			<shortdescription>
				Two vertical shifts of the graph of the square root function,
				one up and one down.
			</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/vshifts.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Vertical scaling</title>

<p>
If we take an <q>old</q> function and multiply every output by some fixed, positive scale factor,
we create a <q>new</q> function whose graph has been stretched away from the horizontal axis
(if the scale factor is greater than <m>1</m>)
or compressed towards the horizontal axis
(if the scale factor is less than <m>1</m>).
Accordingly, for
<me> g(t) = k f(t) </me>,
we call <m>g</m> a <term>vertical scaling</term> of <m>f</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-vscale">
	<title>Vertical scalings of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph either of
	<md><mrow> g(t) \amp = 2 \sqrt{t} \amp h(t) \amp = \frac{\sqrt{t}}{2} </mrow></md>,
	again we relate each of them to the graph of the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>,
	and again focus on anchor points at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(0) \amp = 0                  \amp f(1) \amp = 1                            </mrow>
		<mrow> g(0) \amp = 2 f(0) = 0         \amp g(1) \amp = 2 f(1) = 2                   </mrow>
		<mrow> h(0) \amp = \frac{f(0)}{2} = 0 \amp h(1) \amp = \frac{f(1)}{2} = \frac{1}{2} </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-vscales">
		<caption>
			Two vertical scales of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>,
			one stretched and one compressed.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-vscales" width="60%">
			<shortdescription>
				Two vertical scales of the graph of the square root function,
				one stretched and one compressed.
			</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/vscales.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Vertical reflection</title>

<p>
If we take an <q>old</q> function and change the sign of every output,
we create a <q>new</q> function whose graph has been reflected in the horizontal axis.
Accordingly, for
<me> g(t) = - f(t) </me>,
we call <m>g</m> a <term>vertical reflection</term> of <m>f</m>.
Similarly,
if we have
<me> g(t) = k f(t) </me>
with <m>k</m> negative,
then <m>g</m> will be both a scaling and reflection of <m>f</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-vrefl">
	<title>Vertical reflection of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph
	<me> g(t) = - \sqrt{t} </me>
	again we relate it to the graph of the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>,
	and again focus on anchor points at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(0) \amp = 0                  \amp f(1) \amp = 1           </mrow>
		<mrow> g(0) \amp = - f(0) = 0         \amp g(1) \amp = - f(1) = -1 </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-vrefl">
		<caption> Vertical reflection of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-vrefl" width="60%">
			<shortdescription> Vertical reflection of the graph of the square root function. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/vrefl.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsubsection>

<conclusion>
	<title>Summary of vertical transformations</title>

	<assemblage>
		<title>The three types of vertical transformations</title>
		<p><ul>

			<li><title>Shifts</title><p>
				For a positive constant,
				adding that constant to a function shifts its graph up by that amount,
				while subtracting that constant shifts its graph down.
			</p></li>

			<li><title>Scaling</title><p>
				Multiplying a function by a positive scale factor that is greater than one stretches the graph away from the horizontal axis by that factor,
				while a positive scale factor that is less than one compresses the graph towards the horizontal axis.
			</p></li>

			<li><title>Reflection</title><p>
				Multiplying a function by a negative scale factor (or by <m>-1</m>)
				reflects the graph in the horizontal axis (as well as any scaling effect).
			</p></li>

		</ul></p>
	</assemblage>

</conclusion>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Horizontal transformations</title>

<introduction><p>
	Vertical shifts and scales follow an intuitive pattern:
	<ul>
		<li> adding shifts up while subtracting shifts down </li>
		<li>
			a scale factor greater than one stretches while a scale factor less than one compresses.
		</li>
	</ul>
	We will see that horizontal shifts and scales reverse these patterns.
	For that reason,
	we will investigate horizontal shifts in terms of <em>subtracting</em> either a positive or negative shift term
	and horizontal scales in terms of <em>dividing</em> by a scale factor that is either greater or less than one.
</p></introduction>

<subsubsection>
<title>Horizontal shift</title>

<p>
If we subtract a positive constant from the independent variable <em>before</em> using it as the input for a function,
we are essentially causing output values to occur <q>later.</q>
For example,
for <m>g(t) = f(t - 2)</m>,
the <q>old</q> function's initial output value <m>f(0)</m> occurs at <m>t = 2</m> for the <q>new</q> function:
<me> g(2) = f(2 - 2) = f(0) </me>.
So subtracting a positive constant from the independent variable shifts the graph to the right by that amount.
</p>

<p>
On the other hand,
if we subtract a negative constant from the independent variable
(so, in effect, <em>adding</em> a positive constant),
we cause output values to occur <q>earlier</q>.
For example,
for <m>g(t) = f\bbrac{t - (-2)}</m>,
the initial value of the <q>new</q> function is the same as the <q>old</q> function's value at <m>t = 2</m>:
<me> g(0) = f\bbrac{0 - (-2)} = f(2) </me>.
So subtracting a negative constant from the independent variable shifts the graph to the left by that amount.
</p>

<p>
In either case,
we call the <q>new</q> function a <term>horizontal shift</term> of the <q>old</q> function.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-hshift">
	<title>Horizontal shifts of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph either of
	<md><mrow>
		g(t) \amp = \sqrt{t - 2}
		\amp
		h(t) \amp = \sqrt{t + 2} = \sqrt{t - (-2)}
	</mrow></md>,
	we relate each of them to the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>.
	Now when we choose and track anchor points
	(again at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m> for <m>f</m>),
	we want to determine what new independent variable value will produce the same output.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(0)  \amp = 0                          \amp f(1)  \amp = 1                         </mrow>
		<mrow> g(2)  \amp = f(2 - 2) = f(0)            \amp g(3)  \amp = f(3 - 2) = f(1)           </mrow>
		<mrow> h(-2) \amp = f\bbrac{-2 - (- 2)} = f(0) \amp h(-1) \amp = f\bbrac{-1 - (-2)} = f(1) </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-hshifts">
		<caption>
			Two horizontal shifts of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>,
			one right and one left.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-hshifts" width="77%">
			<shortdescription>
				Two horizontal shifts of the graph of the square root function,
				one right and one left.
			</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/hshifts.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Horizontal scaling</title>

<p>
If we divide the independent variable by a positive constant that is greater than 1 before using it as the input for a function,
we again are causing output values to occur <q>later,</q>
at least for positive inputs.
For example,
for <m>g(t) = f(t/2)</m>,
the value <m>f(1)</m> achieved by the <q>old</q> function at <m>t = 1</m> won't be achieved by the <q>new</q> function until <m>t = 2</m>:
<me> g(2) = f(2 / 2) = f(1) </me>.
However, this effect is symmetric about the vertical axis <mdash />
using our same example <m>g(t) = f(t/2)</m>
the value <m>f(-1)</m> achieved by the <q>old</q> function at <m>t = -1</m> is achieved by the <q>new</q> function until <m>t = -2</m>:
<me> g(-2) = f(-2 / 2) = f(-1) </me>.
Overall, the effect is to stretch the graph of the <q>old</q> function away from the vertical axis.
</p>

<p>
Dividing the independent variable by a positive constant that is less than 1 has the opposite effect,
so that outputs of the old function are <q>pulled in</q> towards the vertical axis.
For example,
for <m>g(t) = f\bbrac{t / 0.5}</m>,
the output value of the <q>old</q> function at <m>t = 2</m> becomes the output value of the <q>new</q> function at <m>t = 1</m>:
<me> g(1) = f(1 / 0.5) = f(2) </me>.
Again, the effect is symmetric about the vertical axis,
so that the overall effect is to compress the graph of the <q>old</q> function towards the vertical axis.
</p>

<p>
In either case,
we call the <q>new</q> function a <term>horizontal scale</term> of the <q>old</q> function.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-hscale">
	<title>Horizontal scalings of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph either of
	<md><mrow> g(t) \amp = \sqrt{t / 2} \amp h(t) \amp = \sqrt{2 t} = \sqrt{t / 0.5} </mrow></md>,
	again we relate each of them to the graph of the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>.
	And again when we track anchor points
	(again at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m> for <m>f</m>),
	we want to determine what new independent variable value will produce the same output.
	But we can immediately say that the anchor point at <m>t = 0</m> won't move,
	so we'll focus on the one at <m>t = 1</m>.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(1)   \amp = 1                               </mrow>
		<mrow> g(2)   \amp = f(2 / 2) = f(1)                 </mrow>
		<mrow> h(1/2) \amp = f\bbrac{ (1/2) / (1/2) } = f(1) </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-hscales">
		<caption>
			Two horizontal scales of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>,
			one stretched and one compressed.
		</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-hscales" width="89.7%">
			<shortdescription>
				Two horizontal scales of the graph of the square root function,
				one stretched and one compressed.
			</shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/hscales.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<remark><p>
	Sometimes it is possible to re-interpret a horizontal scale as a vertical scale or vice versa,
	depending on the algebraic properties of the function's formula.
	For example, for
	<me> g(t) = \sqrt{\frac{t}{2}} = \frac{\sqrt{t}}{\sqrt{2}} </me>
	from <xref ref="example-funcs-hscale" />,
	we could interpret the <q>new</q> function as either a horizontal stretch by a factor of <m>2</m> or as a vertical compression by a factor of <m>\sqrt{2}</m>.
</p></remark>

</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
<title>Horizontal reflection</title>

<p>
If we take an <q>old</q> function and change the sign of inputs before they are used,
we create a <q>new</q> function whose graph has been reflected in the vertical axis.
Accordingly, for
<me> g(t) = f(- t) </me>,
we call <m>g</m> a <term>horizontal reflection</term> of <m>f</m>.
Similarly,
if we have
<me> g(t) = f(t / c) </me>
with <m>c</m> negative,
then <m>g</m> will be both a scaling and reflection of <m>f</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-hrefl">
	<title>Horizontal reflection of the square root function</title>

	<p>
	To graph
	<me> g(t) = \sqrt{- t} </me>
	again we relate it to the graph of the function <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t} </m>.
	It may seem like the formula for <m>g(t)</m> makes no sense,
	since the square root of a negative number is undefined.
	However,
	we are implicitly also reflecting the domain of <m>f</m> to create the domain of <m>g</m>:
	if <m>t \le 0</m>, then <m>- t \ge 0</m>,
	and in this case <m>\sqrt{- t}</m> will make sense.
	</p>

	<p>
	Again we'll focus on anchor points at <m>t = 0</m> and <m>t = 1</m>,
	and again for each anchor point we need to determine what new independent variable value will produce the same output.
	<md>
		<mrow> f(0) \amp = 0      \amp f(1)   \amp = 1                     </mrow>
		<mrow> g(- 0) \amp = f(0) \amp g(- 1) \amp = f\bbrac{-(-1)} = f(1) </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-funcs-hrefl">
		<caption> Horizontal reflection of the graph of <m>f(t) = \sqrt{t}</m>. </caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-hrefl" width="85.0%">
			<shortdescription> Horizontal reflection of the graph of the square root function. </shortdescription>
			<!-- TODO description -->
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/hrefl.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsubsection>

<conclusion>
	<title>Summary of horizontal transformations</title>

	<assemblage>
		<title>The three types of horizontal transformations</title>
		<p><ul>

		<li><title>Shifts</title><p>
			Subtracting a positive constant from the independent variable of a function shifts its graph to the right by that amount,
			while subtracting a negative constant shifts its graph to the left.
		</p></li>

		<li><title>Scaling</title><p>
			Dividing the independent variable of a function by a positive scale factor that is greater than one stretches the graph away from the vertical axis by that factor,
			while dividing by a positive scale factor that is less than one compresses the graph towards the vertical axis.
		</p></li>

		<li><title>Reflection</title><p>
			Replacing the independent variable in a function by its negative reflects the graph in the vertical axis.
		</p></li>

		</ul></p>
	</assemblage>

</conclusion>

</subsection>

</section>

